-- Swedish cbanker af Jochnick says more action on household debt needed
-- 
-- Fri Jan 31, 2014 02:16AM EST
-- None



STOCKHOLM, Jan 31 (Reuters) - Sweden needs to take futher measures to reduce the threat of  high levels of household debt to the economy, central bank First Deputy Governor Kerstin af Jochnick said on Friday.

The majority of rate-setters on the Riksbank board have been concerned about levels of household debt in Sweden that at around 170 percent of disposable income are among the highest in Europe. "Action is needed now to reduce the risks of household indebtedness," af Jochnick said in the text of a speech. She said problems associated with household debt could affect the Riksbank's ability to carry out its job of ensuring price and financial stability.